Cannabis Test Results Analysis — Detecting Hemp-Derived Conversion Products¶

Summary¶

Four of 28 cannabis products tested show moderate-to-high likelihood of containing THC converted from hemp-derived CBD rather than extracted from cannabis.

Product Finding Confidence
Rockin Extracts Cartridge D10-THC at 3.35% High
Nerd Bar Disposable D8-THC at 1.31% High
Dutch Botanicals Cartridge D8-THC at 1.09% High
Cali Blaze Pre-Roll CBDa + Methanol (428 ppm) Moderate

Eight additional products show weaker signals (CBDa alone or trace solvents) that warrant further scrutiny but do not meet the same threshold.

Context¶

CBD-to-THC conversion exploits a gap in the 2018 Farm Bill. A 2021 study of 27 commercial 8-THC products found all contained unlabeled byproducts, none had accurate labels and all contained heavy metals.

Market Trend¶

The reference data spans November 2024 October 2025. Detection rates for conversion markers declined significantly:

  • D10-THC: From 2.6% to 0.2% of samples
  • Methanol: From 9% to <1% of samples

Testing volume drops only ~19% over the same period, so the decline in detection could suggest a real market shiftpossibly due to improved enforcement or producer compliance. Or it could be explained by something like a change in lab client mix.

Identification Method¶

Test samples are compared against ~24,000 licensed cannabis samples. Conversion products leave a chemical signature:

  • D8-THC and D10-THC appear together 28 more often than expectedco-produced in the same reaction
  • Their concentrations correlate strongly (r = 0.94)more D8 tends to mean more D10
  • Cannabis-based products show no such patternD9-THC and THCa have zero correlation (r 0)

The patterns match forensic research on CBD isomerization.

Findings by Confidence Level¶

High Confidence — D8-THC or D10-THC detected¶

Both compounds are rare in natural cannabis (<1% of samples), but scientifically established byproducts of CBD isomerization.

Product Compound Concentration
Rockin Extracts Cartridge D10-THC 3.35%
Nerd Bar Disposable D8-THC 1.31%
Dutch Botanicals Cartridge D8-THC 1.09%

Moderate Confidence — CBDa + process solvent¶

CBDa is the acidic precursor in raw hemp. Its presence in a finished product, combined with a solvent used in conversion chemistry, could suggest incomplete processing of hemp material.

Product CBDa Solvent
Cali Blaze Pre-Roll 0.10% Methanol 428 ppm

Lower Confidence — CBDa only¶

CBDa alone could indicate hemp material, but the data is less definitive.

  • Twax Pre-Roll (0.08%)
  • Juicy Infused Joint (0.09%)

Inconclusive — trace solvents only¶

Several products show low-level solvent detections below the threshold for comparison to reference data.

Background: CBD-to-THC Conversion¶

Process¶

CBD converts to THC when treated with acid and heat. The reaction, documented since the 1940s, produces:

  • 9-THC (the target)
  • 8-THC (a major byproduct)
  • 10-THC (a minor byproduct)
  • Various other isomers

Regulatory Gap¶

The 2018 Farm Bill legalized hemp and its derivatives. Products made by converting hemp CBD to THC may fall outside state cannabis regulations while containing psychoactive compounds.

Detection Method¶

When D8-THC and D10-THC appear together at elevated rates, it suggests shared chemical originlikely from the same reaction, not from the plant. Co-occurrence rates quantify how often two compounds appear in the same sample, versus how often expected by chance.

In the reference data:

  • D8-THC and D10-THC co-occur 28 more than expected
  • D9-THC and THCa (natural forms) co-occur at expected rates

The contrast is a fingerprint, of sorts.

Methodology¶

The analysis compared 28 test samples (Kaycha Labs) against ~24,000 reference samples (Bona Fide Labs).

Steps:

  1. Identified co-occurrence patterns in reference data
  2. Measured concentration correlations between compounds
  3. Applied discovered patterns to flag test samples
  4. Used principal component analysis to visualize outliers

Markers used:

  • D8-THC, D10-THC (conversion byproducts)
  • CBDa (hemp precursor)
  • Methanol, Ethyl Acetate, Heptane (process solvents)

Data Cleaning Function: clean_value¶

Standardizes measurement values across datasets:

  • Returns 0 for blank values or text indicating non-detection ("ND", "NT", "N/A", "<LOQ")
  • Converts string numbers to floats
In [2]:
def clean_value(val):
    
    # For blank measurement values, return zero
    if pd.isna(val): return 0.0

    # For values with text that needs to be cleaned...        
    if isinstance(val, str):
        
        # Get rid of extra spaces
        val = val.strip()

        # For values of ND (Not Detected), NT (Not Tested) and N/A (Not Applicable), return zero
        if val in ['ND', 'NT', 'N/A']: return 0.0

        # For values with a "less than" (<), return zero
        if val.startswith('<'): return 0.0

    # Try to turn it into a number
    try:
        return float(val)

    # If anything isn't resolved to a number here, or returns an error, return zero    
    except:
        return 0.0

Loading Reference Data¶

Load the reference database from Bona Fide Labs, which contains:

  • Potency data: Cannabinoid concentrations (D9-THC, THCa, CBD, CBDa, D8-THC, D10-THC, etc.)
  • Solvent data: Residual solvent concentrations (Methanol, Ethanol, Heptane, etc.)

Data structure:

  • Each sample has a unique Lab Sample ID that ties cannabinoid and solvent results together
  • Pivot the data so each row is one sample, each column is one analyte

Baselines created:

  • Vapes/Concentrates (~10,000 samples): For comparing vape test samples
  • Flower/Buds (~13,000 samples): For comparing preroll test samples
  • Full Reference (~24,000 samples): For discovery phase analysis

Note: The discovery analysis uses the full reference dataset to maximize statistical weight.

Discovery analysis — identifying a chemical fingerprint¶

Analysis of ~24,000 reference samples to identify patterns that distinguish conversion products from natural cannabis.

Co-Occurrence Analysis¶

The question: If D8-THC and D10-THC are both byproducts of CBD isomerization, they should appear together far more often than chance would predict.

The method: A co-occurrence ratio measures how often two compounds appear together versus how often expected if they were independent.

  • Ratio >> 1: Compounds appear together more than expected, suggesting shared origin
  • Ratio 1: Random co-occurrence, no relationship
  • Ratio << 1: Compounds appear together less than expected, mutually exclusive

See: Acid-catalyzed CBD isomerization produces D8-THC, D9-THC and a compound suspected to be D10-THC across all tested reaction pathways.

How it works:

  1. Each sample in the reference data has a unique Lab Sample ID that ties all test results together
  2. The data is pivoted so each row = one sample, each column = one chemical
  3. For every pair of chemicals, count how many samples have both detected

Co-occurrence Ratio:

  • Expected co-occurrence = P(Chemical A) P(Chemical B) Total Samples
    • How often they'd appear together if completely independent
  • Ratio = Actual co-occurrences Expected co-occurrences
    • ~1x = random chance (no relationship)
    • >1x = appear together more than expected (associated)
    • 28x = appear together 28 times more often than random (strong chemical link)

Significance:

  • D8-THC and D10-THC showing 28 co-occurrence suggests they almost always appear together
  • Both are byproducts of the same CBD-to-THC isomerization process
  • Normal cannabis chemicals (D9-THC and THCa) show ~1 co-occurrence with conversion markers

Important limitation: Solvent detection threshold

The reference lab appears to have a Limit of Quantification (LOQ) of ~100 ppm for solvents:

  • "Detected" in reference data = solvent concentration 100 ppm
  • Values between 0-100 ppm are not detected
  • The reference data has no values between 0 and 100 ppm for any solvent

Impact on analysis:

  • Cannabinoid co-occurrence patterns are likely valid (similar sensitivity in both datasets)
  • Solvent co-occurrence patterns reflect high-level detection only (100 ppm)
  • If the reference lab could detect lower levels, different patterns might emerge
  • The co-occurrence ratios for cannabinoid-solvent pairs are conservativethey only capture cases where solvents are present at high concentrations

from scipy.stats import fisher_exact

def format_pval(p):
    """Format p-value for display: scientific notation for tiny values, otherwise rounded."""
    if p < 0.0001:
        return f'{p:.1e}'
    elif p < 0.01:
        return f'{p:.4f}'
    else:
        return f'{p:.3f}'

# Full reference (both baselines combined)
temp_cann = pd.read_excel('Exported Potency Data.xlsx', converters={'Numeric Result': str})
temp_solv = pd.read_excel('Exported Residual Solvents Data.xlsx', converters={'Numeric Result': str})
temp_cann['Clean_Result'] = temp_cann['Numeric Result'].apply(clean_value)
temp_solv['Clean_Result'] = temp_solv['Numeric Result'].apply(clean_value)

df_cann_full = temp_cann.pivot_table(index='Lab Sample ID', columns='Analyte', values='Clean_Result', aggfunc='max')
df_solv_full = temp_solv.pivot_table(index='Lab Sample ID', columns='Analyte', values='Clean_Result', aggfunc='max')
full_ref = df_cann_full.join(df_solv_full, how='outer').fillna(0)

cannabinoids = ['delta-8-THC', 'delta-10-THC', 'delta-9-THC', 'CBDa', 'CBD', 'CBN', 'CBG', 'THCa']
solvents = ['Methanol', 'Ethanol', 'Heptane', 'Toluene', 'Ethyl Acetate', 'Total Butanes', 
            'Isopropyl Alcohol', 'Hexanes', 'Pentanes', 'Acetone', 'Benzene']

cannabinoids = [c for c in cannabinoids if c in full_ref.columns]
solvents = [s for s in solvents if s in full_ref.columns]

n_total = len(full_ref)
results = []

for cann in cannabinoids:
    for solv in solvents:
        has_cann = full_ref[cann] > 0
        has_solv = full_ref[solv] > 0
        
        n_cann = has_cann.sum()
        n_solv = has_solv.sum()
        n_both = (has_cann & has_solv).sum()
        
        # Expected co-occurrence if independent
        p_cann = n_cann / n_total
        p_solv = n_solv / n_total
        expected = p_cann * p_solv * n_total
        
        # Co-occurrence ratio (how many times more often than expected)
        ratio = n_both / expected if expected > 0 else 0
        
        # Fisher's exact test for statistical significance
        n_cann_only = n_cann - n_both
        n_solv_only = n_solv - n_both
        n_neither = n_total - n_cann - n_solv + n_both
        contingency = [[n_both, n_cann_only], [n_solv_only, n_neither]]
        _, p_value = fisher_exact(contingency, alternative='greater')
        
        # Only record if there's at least 1 co-occurrence
        if n_both > 0:
            results.append({
                'Cannabinoid': cann,
                'Solvent': solv,
                'Co-occurrences': n_both,
                'Expected': round(expected, 1),
                'Ratio': round(ratio, 1),
                'p-value': p_value
            })

# Convert to DataFrame and sort by ratio
results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)
results_df = results_df.sort_values('Ratio', ascending=False)
results_df['p-value'] = results_df['p-value'].apply(format_pval)

# Cannabinoid-cannabinoid co-occurrence
all_cannabinoids = [c for c in ['delta-9-THC', 'THCa', 'delta-8-THC', 'delta-10-THC', 'CBD', 'CBDa', 'CBN', 'CBG'] 
                    if c in full_ref.columns]

cann_cann_results = []
for i, c1 in enumerate(all_cannabinoids):
    for c2 in all_cannabinoids[i+1:]:  # Avoid duplicates
        has_c1 = full_ref[c1] > 0
        has_c2 = full_ref[c2] > 0
        n_c1 = has_c1.sum()
        n_c2 = has_c2.sum()
        n_both = (has_c1 & has_c2).sum()
        expected = (n_c1 / n_total) * (n_c2 / n_total) * n_total
        ratio = n_both / expected if expected > 0 else 0
        
        # Fisher's exact test for statistical significance
        n_c1_only = n_c1 - n_both
        n_c2_only = n_c2 - n_both
        n_neither = n_total - n_c1 - n_c2 + n_both
        contingency = [[n_both, n_c1_only], [n_c2_only, n_neither]]
        _, p_value = fisher_exact(contingency, alternative='greater')
        
        cann_cann_results.append({
            'Pair': f"{c1} + {c2}",
            'Co-occur': n_both,
            'Expected': round(expected, 1),
            'Ratio': round(ratio, 1),
            'p-value': p_value
        })

cann_cann_df = pd.DataFrame(cann_cann_results).sort_values('Ratio', ascending=False)
cann_cann_df['p-value'] = cann_cann_df['p-value'].apply(format_pval)

# Display without index
cann_cann_df[['Pair', 'Co-occur', 'Expected', 'Ratio', 'p-value']].reset_index(drop=True)

# Co-occurrence heatmaps

# Define chemical groups
cann_list = ['delta-8-THC', 'delta-10-THC', 'CBD', 'CBDa', 'CBN', 'delta-9-THC', 'THCa']
solv_list = ['Methanol', 'Ethanol', 'Heptane', 'Toluene', 'Ethyl Acetate', 'Hexanes']

# Filter to columns that exist
cann_list = [c for c in cann_list if c in full_ref.columns]
solv_list = [s for s in solv_list if s in full_ref.columns]



def calc_cooccur_ratio(df, chem1, chem2):
    n_total = len(df)
    has_1 = df[chem1] > 0
    has_2 = df[chem2] > 0
    n_1 = has_1.sum()
    n_2 = has_2.sum()
    n_both = (has_1 & has_2).sum()
    expected = (n_1 / n_total) * (n_2 / n_total) * n_total
    if expected > 0 and n_both > 0:
        return n_both / expected
    return np.nan

def build_matrix(df, row_chems, col_chems):
    matrix = np.zeros((len(row_chems), len(col_chems)))
    for i, r in enumerate(row_chems):
        for j, c in enumerate(col_chems):
            if r == c:
                matrix[i, j] = np.nan
            else:
                matrix[i, j] = calc_cooccur_ratio(df, r, c)
    return matrix

def plot_heatmap(matrix, row_labels, col_labels, title, ax):
    short_row = [l.replace('delta-', 'D').replace('-THC', '') for l in row_labels]
    short_col = [l.replace('delta-', 'D').replace('-THC', '') for l in col_labels]
    
    with np.errstate(divide='ignore', invalid='ignore'):
        log_matrix = np.log2(matrix)
    
    cmap = sns.diverging_palette(220, 20, as_cmap=True)
    sns.heatmap(log_matrix, 
                xticklabels=short_col, 
                yticklabels=short_row,
                annot=matrix,
                fmt='.1f',
                cmap=cmap,
                center=0,
                vmin=-2, vmax=5,
                cbar_kws={'label': 'log2(Co-occur Ratio)'},
                ax=ax,
                linewidths=0.5,
                annot_kws={'size': 8})
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=11, fontweight='bold')

Concentration Correlation Analysis: Are the amounts related?¶

The co-occurrence analysis addresses: do the chemicals appear together? (yes/no detection)

A separate question: when they do appear together, are their concentrations related?

The difference:

  • Co-occurrence = both chemicals detected (any amount > 0)
  • Concentration correlation = when one is high, is the other also high?

Significance:

  • If D8 and D10 are produced by the same chemical reaction, their concentrations should be tightly linked
  • If D9 and THCa are produced by independent biological processes, their concentrations should be independent

Pearson's r (correlation coefficient):

  • r = 1.0 = perfect positive correlation (concentrations move together exactly)
  • r = 0.7+ = strong correlation (concentrations are linked)
  • r ~ 0 = no correlation (concentrations are independent)
  • r = -1.0 = perfect negative correlation (one goes up, other goes down)

Note on sample size: Correlation coefficients are less reliable with small sample sizes. With n < 30, even a high r value may not be statistically robust. The patterns matter more than the precise r values.

Expected findings:

  • Conversion products (D8, D10, CBD): r > 0.7 - same chemical origin
  • Natural cannabis (D9, THCa): r ~ 0 - independent biosynthesis

Concentration ratios:

Beyond correlation, the ratio of concentrations for key pairs provides additional insight:

  • D8:D10 - Are the byproducts produced in consistent proportions?
  • D8:CBD and D8:CBDa - How much precursor remains after conversion?
  • D9:THCa - Natural cannabis baseline for comparison

Coefficient of Variation (CV%):

  • Measures how consistent the ratio is across all samples
  • Low CV (<50%): Consistent ratio, suggesting a single controlled chemical process
  • High CV (>100%): Variable ratio, suggesting multiple conversion methods or sources
  • The D8:D10 ratio can serve as a "fingerprint" for products from the same process

Important: Product Type Matters

The D9:THCa ratio spans 10,000+ samples across all product types (flower, concentrates, edibles), which inflates variability. Breaking this down by matrix provides a fair comparison:

  • Flower/Shake/Trim: Consistent low ratio (~0.04-0.06) because THCa hasn't been decarboxylated
  • Concentrates: Extreme variability because decarboxylation varies by process

In contrast, D8/D10/CBD pairs are 95-100% concentrates - they're already in a single product category, so no breakdown is needed.

# Concentration correlation: when both are present, do amounts correlate?

conc_pairs = [
    ('delta-8-THC', 'delta-10-THC'),
    ('delta-8-THC', 'CBD'),
    ('delta-10-THC', 'CBD'),
    ('delta-8-THC', 'CBDa'),
    ('delta-10-THC', 'CBDa'),
    ('delta-9-THC', 'THCa'),
    ('delta-9-THC', 'CBN'),
]

corr_results = []
for c1, c2 in conc_pairs:
    if c1 not in full_ref.columns or c2 not in full_ref.columns:
        continue
    mask = (full_ref[c1] > 0) & (full_ref[c2] > 0)
    subset = full_ref[mask]
    n = len(subset)
    if n >= 3:
        r, p = stats.pearsonr(subset[c1], subset[c2])
        corr_results.append({'Pair': f'{c1} + {c2}', 'N': n, 'r': round(r, 3), 'p': p})

corr_df = pd.DataFrame(corr_results)
corr_df['Sig'] = corr_df['p'].apply(format_pval)
corr_df[['Pair', 'N', 'r', 'Sig']]

Time Series Analysis: Are conversion products becoming more or less common?¶

The reference data spans 12 months (November 2024 October 2025).

Metrics:

  • Detection rate: Percentage of samples each month with detectable levels of each compound
  • Cannabinoids: D8-THC, D10-THC (conversion byproducts), CBDa (hemp precursor)
  • Solvents: Methanol, Ethyl Acetate (process solvents used in conversion chemistry)

The data provides context: if conversion products are declining in the reference data, the trend suggests either improved enforcement, better producer compliance or market shifts.

# Time series analysis: detection rates over time

# Load raw data with timestamps
ts_cann = pd.read_excel('Exported Potency Data.xlsx', converters={'Numeric Result': str})
ts_solv = pd.read_excel('Exported Residual Solvents Data.xlsx', converters={'Numeric Result': str})
ts_cann['Clean_Result'] = ts_cann['Numeric Result'].apply(clean_value)
ts_solv['Clean_Result'] = ts_solv['Numeric Result'].apply(clean_value)

def get_monthly_stats(df, analyte, max_valid=100):
    """Calculate monthly detection rates for an analyte.
    
    Args:
        max_valid: Cap for valid values (default 100%). Values above this are
                   treated as data entry errors and excluded from mean calculations.
    """
    subset = df[df['Analyte'] == analyte].copy()
    if len(subset) == 0:
        return None
    
    # Cap outliers for mean calculation (same as concentration scatter plots)
    subset['Capped_Result'] = subset['Clean_Result'].apply(lambda x: x if x <= max_valid else np.nan)
    
    monthly = subset.groupby('Analysis Period').agg(
        total=('Clean_Result', 'count'),
        detections=('Clean_Result', lambda x: (x > 0).sum()),
        mean_conc=('Capped_Result', lambda x: x[(x > 0) & (x.notna())].mean() if ((x > 0) & (x.notna())).any() else 0)
    ).sort_index()
    monthly['rate'] = (monthly['detections'] / monthly['total'] * 100)
    monthly['month'] = pd.to_datetime(monthly.index + '-01')
    return monthly

Application — flagging suspicious products¶

Application of the markers discovered above to 28 independent test samples. Any product showing the identified patterns (D8-THC, D10-THC, CBDa, process solvents) gets flagged for further investigation.

Note: Solvent Detection Limits¶

Before applying markers to test samples, a limitation in the solvent analysis must be noted:

The reference data and test data use different analytical sensitivities:

Solvent Reference LOQ Reference Detections Test Data Sensitivity
Methanol ~100 ppm 105 samples (3.5%) <1 ppm
Ethyl Acetate ~100 ppm 28 samples (0.9%) <1 ppm
Heptane ~100 ppm 2 samples (0.07%) <1 ppm
Toluene ~100 ppm 0 samples (0%) <1 ppm

Implications:

  • The reference lab's Limit of Quantification (LOQ) is approximately 100 ppm for solvents
  • The test data uses a more sensitive method that can detect solvents at <1 ppm
  • Most test sample solvent detections fall below the reference LOQ
  • Test values below 100 ppm cannot be statistically compared to the reference distribution

Our approach - Tiered Flagging:

  • Tier 1 (High Confidence): Test value 100 ppm, exceeds reference LOQ, can be compared to reference
  • Tier 2 (Detection Only): Test value >0 but <100 ppm, detected but below reference LOQ, uncertain significance

The limitation does not affect:

  • Cannabinoid analysis (both datasets have similar sensitivity)
  • Cannabinoid-cannabinoid co-occurrence patterns (e.g., D8+D10 at 28x enrichment)

The limitation does affect:

  • Cannabinoid-solvent co-occurrence patterns (reference only sees solvents 100 ppm)
  • The discovery phase findings for solvents reflect high-level detection only

Applying Discovered Markers to Test Samples¶

Application of the markers identified in the discovery phase to our independent test samples:

  1. Load test data from Kaycha Labs
  2. Flag samples that match suspicious patterns:
    • Primary: D8-THC, D10-THC or CBDa detection
    • Secondary: Unusual solvents (with tiered confidence based on LOQ)
  3. Classify samples as Vape or Preroll
  4. Calculate Z-scores against appropriate baseline (meaningful only for values above LOQ)

Multivariate Analysis¶

A Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to see how test samples compare to the entire reference data set, when considering multiple chemicals simultaneouslya "chemical fingerprint comparison"where products from CBD conversion should cluster away from normal cannabis.

Critical methodological point: PCA is fit to the reference data (defining what "normal" looks like), then test samples are projected into that space. The result shows which test samples fall outside the normal reference distribution.

THREE analyses explore different perspectives:

Analysis A: Focused cannabinoid markers (D8, D10, CBDa)

  • D8-THC, D10-THC, CBDa concentrations only
  • The specific markers identified in discovery analysis
  • Most methodologically sound - both datasets have comparable sensitivity

Analysis B: Cannabinoids + all Tier 1 solvents (100 ppm)

  • Features: D8-THC, D10-THC, CBDa + all solvents with values 100 ppm
  • Includes: Methanol, Ethanol, Acetone, Heptane, Toluene, Ethyl Acetate, Isopropyl Alcohol
  • Reference filtered to samples with at least one Tier 1 solvent detection
  • Fair comparison - both labs can detect at this level

Analysis C: Expanded cannabinoid profile (D8, D10, CBDa, CBD, CBN)

  • Features: Five cannabinoids that may indicate conversion or degradation
  • CBD: Precursor for D8/D10 conversion
  • CBN: Degradation product (may indicate age or processing)
  • Provides broader chemical profile view

# PCA: project test samples into reference chemical space

SOLVENT_LOQ = 100

def run_pca_analysis(ref_df, test_df, features):
    """Fit PCA on reference, project test samples."""
    ref_data = pd.DataFrame()
    for f in features:
        ref_data[f] = pd.to_numeric(ref_df[f], errors='coerce').fillna(0) if f in ref_df.columns else 0
    
    test_data = pd.DataFrame()
    for f in features:
        test_data[f] = pd.to_numeric(test_df[f], errors='coerce').fillna(0) if f in test_df.columns else 0
    
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    ref_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(ref_data)
    
    pca = PCA(n_components=2)
    ref_pca = pca.fit_transform(ref_scaled)
    
    test_scaled = scaler.transform(test_data)
    test_pca = pca.transform(test_scaled)
    
    loadings = pd.DataFrame(pca.components_.T, columns=['PC1', 'PC2'], index=features)
    var_explained = pca.explained_variance_ratio_ * 100
    ref_centroid = ref_pca.mean(axis=0)
    ref_std = ref_pca.std(axis=0)
    
    return ref_pca, test_pca, loadings, var_explained, ref_centroid, ref_std

# Analysis A: Focused Cannabinoid Markers
features_A = ['delta-8-THC', 'delta-10-THC', 'CBDa']
ref_pca_A, test_pca_A, loadings_A, var_A, centroid_A, std_A = run_pca_analysis(full_ref, final_df, features_A)

final_df['PC1_Z_A'] = (test_pca_A[:, 0] - centroid_A[0]) / std_A[0]
final_df['PC2_Z_A'] = (test_pca_A[:, 1] - centroid_A[1]) / std_A[1]
final_df['PCA_Dist_A'] = np.sqrt(((test_pca_A - centroid_A) ** 2).sum(axis=1))

# Analysis B: Cannabinoids + Tier 1 Solvents
all_solvents = ['Methanol', 'Ethanol', 'Acetone', 'Heptane', 'Toluene', 
                'Ethyl Acetate', 'Isopropyl Alcohol', 'Hexane', 'Benzene']

tier1_flags = []
for solv in all_solvents:
    flag_name = solv.replace(' ', '_') + '_T1'
    tier1_flags.append(flag_name)
    full_ref[flag_name] = (full_ref[solv] >= SOLVENT_LOQ).astype(int) if solv in full_ref.columns else 0
    final_df[flag_name] = (final_df[solv] >= SOLVENT_LOQ).astype(int) if solv in final_df.columns else 0

active_tier1_flags = [f for f in tier1_flags if full_ref[f].sum() > 0]
full_ref['Any_Tier1_Solvent'] = full_ref[tier1_flags].max(axis=1)
ref_with_solvents = full_ref[full_ref['Any_Tier1_Solvent'] == 1].copy()

features_B = ['delta-8-THC', 'delta-10-THC', 'CBDa'] + active_tier1_flags
ref_pca_B, test_pca_B, loadings_B, var_B, centroid_B, std_B = run_pca_analysis(ref_with_solvents, final_df, features_B)

final_df['PC1_Z_B'] = (test_pca_B[:, 0] - centroid_B[0]) / std_B[0]
final_df['PC2_Z_B'] = (test_pca_B[:, 1] - centroid_B[1]) / std_B[1]
final_df['PCA_Dist_B'] = np.sqrt(((test_pca_B - centroid_B) ** 2).sum(axis=1))

# Analysis C: Expanded Cannabinoid Profile
features_C = ['delta-8-THC', 'delta-10-THC', 'CBDa', 'CBD', 'CBN']
ref_pca_C, test_pca_C, loadings_C, var_C, centroid_C, std_C = run_pca_analysis(full_ref, final_df, features_C)

final_df['PC1_Z_C'] = (test_pca_C[:, 0] - centroid_C[0]) / std_C[0]
final_df['PC2_Z_C'] = (test_pca_C[:, 1] - centroid_C[1]) / std_C[1]
final_df['PCA_Dist_C'] = np.sqrt(((test_pca_C - centroid_C) ** 2).sum(axis=1))

def plot_pca(ax, ref_pca, test_pca, centroid, var, loadings, title, n_ref):
    """Helper to plot PCA scatter"""
    ax.scatter(ref_pca[:, 0], ref_pca[:, 1], c='#17becf', s=4, alpha=0.35, label=f'Reference (n={n_ref})')
    ax.scatter(test_pca[~flagged_mask, 0], test_pca[~flagged_mask, 1], 
               c='#ff7f0e', s=50, edgecolors='#cc6600', linewidth=0.5, alpha=0.9, label='Test - Not Flagged')
    ax.scatter(test_pca[flagged_mask, 0], test_pca[flagged_mask, 1], 
               c='#d62728', s=70, edgecolors='black', linewidth=0.8, alpha=1.0, label='Test - Flagged')
    for i, (idx, row) in enumerate(final_df.iterrows()):
        if row.get('Any_Flag', False):
            product_name = str(row['Product'])
            short_name = product_name[:10] + '..' if len(product_name) > 10 else product_name
            ax.annotate(short_name, (test_pca[i, 0], test_pca[i, 1]), 
                        xytext=(5, 5), textcoords='offset points', fontsize=5, color='darkred')
    ax.scatter([centroid[0]], [centroid[1]], c='#9467bd', s=100, marker='X', 
               edgecolors='#5c3d7a', linewidths=1.5, alpha=0.7, label='Ref Centroid', zorder=10)
    ax.set_xlabel(f"PC1 ({var[0]:.0f}%): {', '.join(loadings['PC1'].abs().nlargest(2).index)}", fontsize=8)
    ax.set_ylabel(f"PC2 ({var[1]:.0f}%): {', '.join(loadings['PC2'].abs().nlargest(2).index)}", fontsize=8)
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=10, fontweight='bold')
    ax.legend(loc='upper right', fontsize=6)
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)

Chemical Relationship Scatter Plots (Bivariate)¶

PCA works for multivariate analysis, but the axes (PC1, PC2) are hard-to-conceptualize combinations of features. Direct scatter plots show chemical concentrations against each other for easier interpretation.

Row 1: Cannabinoid-Cannabinoid Pairs

  • D8-THC vs D10-THCconversion byproducts (strongest signal)
  • D8-THC vs CBDconversion product vs precursor
  • D8-THC vs CBDaconversion product vs precursor

Row 2: Cannabinoid-Solvent Pairs (With LOQ Caveat)

  • D8-THC vs Methanolconversion product + process solvent
  • CBDa vs Methanolprecursor + process solvent
  • Methanol vs Ethyl Acetatesolvent-solvent relationship

Important: The dashed orange line at 100 ppm marks the reference LOQ threshold.

  • Points above the line = Tier 1 (can be compared to reference data)
  • Points below the line = Tier 2 (detected but below reference sensitivity)

Color coding:

  • Red points: Flagged samples (have suspicious markers)
  • Blue points: Normal samples

        ax.set_ylim(ylim)

    for idx, row in final_df.iterrows():
        if row.get('Any_Flag', False):
            x = x_vals[final_df.index.get_loc(idx)]

Conclusion¶

Four of 28 products show apparent moderate-to-high likelihood of containing hemp-derived THC:

Product Marker Confidence
Rockin Extracts Cartridge D10-THC 3.35% High
Nerd Bar Disposable D8-THC 1.31% High
Dutch Botanicals Cartridge D8-THC 1.09% High
Cali Blaze Pre-Roll CBDa 0.10% + Methanol 428 ppm Moderate

Eight additional products showed weaker signals (CBDa alone or trace solvents).

Key Patterns in Reference Data¶

Pattern Finding Meaning
D8-THC + D10-THC 28 co-occurrence, r = 0.94 Strongest markerco-produced in isomerization
D8-THC + CBD/CBDa 6-8 co-occurrence, r > 0.9 CBD is the precursor
D9-THC + THCa 1 co-occurrence, r = -0.07 Natural cannabis baselineno correlation

The contrast between conversion products (r > 0.9) and natural cannabis (r 0) distinguishes hemp-derived from plant-extracted THC.

See: CBD isomerization produces D8-THC, D9-THC and a compound suspected to be D10-THC across all tested reaction pathways. The D8+D10 co-occurrence observed here matches the documented signature.

Commercial product analysis: A 2021 study tested 27 8-THC vaporizers. All contained reaction byproducts. None had accurate labels. All contained heavy metals.

Time Series: Market trends over 12 months¶

The reference data spans November 2024 October 2025. Detection rates for conversion markers show a clear downward trend:

Marker Peak Rate Recent Rate Change
D10-THC 2.6% 0.2% -92%
D8-THC 0.8% 0.1% -88%
Methanol 9.1% 1.3% -86%
Ethanol 6.7% <1% -85%

Key observation: Testing volume dropped only ~19% over this period. The much larger decline in detection rates (85-92%) suggests a real market shiftnot just reduced testing.

Possible explanations:

  • Improved regulatory enforcement
  • Producer compliance with testing requirements
  • Market shift away from conversion products
  • Supply chain changes

The licensed cannabis market could be becoming cleaner over time, but the flagged products in our test set suggest the problem hasn't been resolved entirely.

Multivariate Analysis¶

Principal component analysis compared test samples against the reference data across several dimensions.

Analysis Features Finding
Focused markers D8, D10, CBDa Rockin Extracts is a statistical outlier
With solvents + Methanol, Ethanol, etc. Rockin Extracts remains outlier
Expanded + CBD, CBN Rockin Extracts outlier; CBD/CBDa drive separation

Flagged Products¶

High confidence (D8-THC or D10-THC detected):

  • Rockin Extracts Cartridge: D10-THC 3.35%
  • Nerd Bar Disposable: D8-THC 1.31%
  • Dutch Botanicals Cartridge: D8-THC 1.09%
  • Cali Blaze Pre-Roll: CBDa 0.10% + Methanol 428 ppm

Lower confidence (CBDa only):

  • Juicy Infused Joint: CBDa 0.09%
  • Twax Pre-Roll: CBDa 0.08%

Inconclusive (trace solvents only): Multiple samples showed solvents below 100 ppmdetected but below the reference data's limit of quantification.

Limitations¶

The reference data and test data use different analytical sensitivities:

  • Reference data LOQ: ~100 ppm (no values between 0-100 ppm exist)
  • Test data sensitivity: <1 ppm

Impact on Analysis:

  • Cannabinoid analysis is fully valid (similar sensitivity)
  • Cannabinoid-cannabinoid co-occurrence patterns are fully valid
  • Solvent analysis requires tiered interpretation:
    • Tier 1 (100 ppm): Can compare to reference
    • Tier 2 (<100 ppm): Detected but cannot determine if unusual

Confidence Summary¶

Confidence Criteria Samples
Highest D10-THC + multivariate outlier Rockin Extracts
High D8-THC detected Nerd Bar, Dutch Botanicals
Moderate CBDa + Tier 1 solvent Cali Blaze Pre-Roll
Moderate CBDa only Twax, Juicy Infused Joint
Uncertain Tier 2 solvent only Multiple samples

Next Steps¶

  1. Products with D8-THC or D10-THC warrant further scrutiny
  2. The D8+D10 co-occurrence pattern is the most reliable indicator
  3. Solvent detections below 100 ppm are inconclusive given reference data detection limit differences
